    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The validated QoI (NIH) must be directly mappable to the decision QoI (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "NIH is the primary experimental observable; RH is computed as the ratio of device NIH to predicate NIH, both predicted by the same model chain. The mapping is direct and the QoI is relevant to the COU decision. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger model is stated to apply when shear-stress exposure is approximately monotonic, a precondition that is satisfied at the nominal validation point but is not examined for the broader COU operating envelope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry and boundary conditions must correspond to the same pump design and fluid used in the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation uses the same FDA generic centrifugal pump CAD geometry, the same blood analogue fluid, and the same solver settings as the COU simulations. Geometric and fluid relevance is confirmed. The validation envelope covers only the nominal operating point; relevance to the four off-nominal COU points is asserted by engineering judgment without a formal check that the theoretical preconditions of the damage model hold across the full operating range."
    },
